{{Infobox book | name = An Inquiry into the Good | title_orig = Zen no kenkyū | translator = | image = File:An Inquiry into the Good.jpg | caption = Cover of an English translation | author = [[Kitaro Nishida]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = Japan | language = Japanese | subject = [[Ethics]] | published ={{plainlist| *1911 (in Japanese) *1960 (in English) }} | media_type = Print | ISBN = 978-0300052336 | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }} '''''An Inquiry into the Good''''', also known as '''''A Study of Good''''', ({{lang-ja|善の研究, Zen no kenkyū}}) is a 1911 book by the Japanese philosopher [[Kitaro Nishida]]. The work has been described as a masterpiece.
==Influence and reception== Graham Parkes, writing in ''[[The Oxford Companion to Philosophy]]'' (2005), described ''An Inquiry into the Good'' as a "masterpiece" that was made possible by the Japanese interest in western philosophy that began with the [[Meiji Restoration]] of 1868. He considered the book "path-breaking" and identified it as Nishida's best known accomplishment.{{sfn|Parkes|2005|pages=458, 659}}
[[Ninian Smart]], writing in ''World Philosophies'' (2008), stated that the book "struck many readers as the first truly creative work by a Japanese that did not merely repeat western ideas, and yet made use of modern thinking and terminology." However, according to Smart, the work was criticized by the philosopher Takahashi Satomi, who found the subjectivism of "pure experience" too psychological.{{sfn|Smart|2008|pages=426, 430}}
